Here's a JavaScript function that uses regular expressions to extract a three-character code from a filename following the specified pattern:
```javascript
function extractThreeCharacterCode(filename) {
    // Check if the filename has the correct format with .usfm extension
    if (!/^[0-9]{2}-[a-zA-Z]{3}\.usfm$/.test(filename)) {
        return "Invalid filename. It should be in the format '57-1Jn.usfm'.";
    }

    // Extract the three-character code using regex
    const match = /-[a-zA-Z0-9]{3}/g.exec(filename);
    if (match) {
        return match[0];
    } else {
        return "No three-character code found.";
    }
}
```
This function first checks if the given `filename` matches the required format: a two-digit number followed by `-`, then a three-letter or digit sequence, and finally `.usfm`. If it does not, it returns an error message. If it's a valid filename, it uses a regular expression (`/-[a-zA-Z0-9]{3}/g`) to find the first occurrence of a match (since there can only be one three-character code in the filename). It then returns the extracted code or "No three-character code found" if no match is found.
